{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645454"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:18:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:18:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18116"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18116"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.69,0.03,0,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10830"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78293"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10830"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18116"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63688"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3000"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25206"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25209"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26860"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78293"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with difficulty in lifting his right arm above his head. He reports that this issue started after he fell off his bicycle two weeks ago. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. When asked to push against a wall, his right scapula protrudes markedly from the back, resembling a wing (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is most likely to have been injured?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Axillary","Long thoracic","Musculocutaneous","Radial","Suprascapular"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic signs of scapular winging, which is most commonly due to injury of the \u003Cstrong\u003Elong thoracic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E. This nerve innervates the serratus anterior muscle, which is responsible for holding the scapula against the thoracic wall. When the long thoracic nerve is damaged, the serratus anterior muscle becomes weak or paralysed, leading to the characteristic winging of the scapula.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles and is typically injured in shoulder dislocations, leading to weakness in shoulder abduction but not scapular winging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emusculocutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the biceps brachii, brachialis, and coracobrachialis muscles, and its injury would result in weakness of elbow flexion and forearm supination, not scapular winging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the muscles of the posterior compartment of the arm and forearm, and its injury typically results in wrist drop, not scapular winging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuprascapular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the supraspinatus and infraspinatus muscles, and its injury would lead to weakness in shoulder abduction and external rotation, not scapular winging.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Winging of the scapula is most commonly caused by injury to the long thoracic nerve.","The long thoracic nerve innervates the serratus anterior muscle, which stabilises the scapula against the thoracic wall.","Damage to the long thoracic nerve can occur due to trauma, surgery, or repetitive activities."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63688"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18116"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21450"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21450"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/kmP6uQMk8kG0OliUZayINYmdcGEiCw.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/kmP6uQMk8kG0OliUZayINYmdcGEiCw.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":532}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63688"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T12:06:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T12:07:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10830"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78293"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"se